                        <div class="intro-course__wapper">
                          <p>
                            A set of vectors is said to be <b>linearly dependent</b> if at least one of the vectors in the set can be defined as a linear combination of other vectors; if no vector in the set can be written in this way, then the vectors are said to be <b>linearly independent</b>.
                          </p>
                          <p> To interpret it geometrically, consider the set of vectors A = {e<sub>x</sub>,e<sub>y</sub>} = {(1,0), (0,1)}. Now, if we try to write (1,0) = c<sub>1</sub>(0,1); c<sub>1</sub> being a constant, we get two equations: 1 = 0 and c<sub>1</sub> = 0 which is not possible (1 &#8800; 0 ).
                            Similarly, if we try to write (0,1) = c<sub>2</sub>(1,0), we get two equations with no solution.
                            Now, since we can not write any vector from this set A as a linear multiple of other vector, we say that e<sub>x</sub> and e<sub>y</sub> are linear independent.
                          </p>
                          <p>Let's see what happens if we take a set of linearly dependent vectors, let's say B = {v<sub>1</sub>, v<sub>2</sub>}= {(1,1), (2,2)}. As we can easily see, (2,2) = 2(1,1) or (1,1) = 0.5(2,2), Therefore, by definition, v<sub>1</sub> and v<sub>2</sub> are linearly dependent.
                          </p>
                          <p>Now, linear depedence and independence has a very beautiful relaionship with the matrix representation of vectors, as discussed below:</p>
                          <p>If we write A = {e<sub>x</sub>,e<sub>y</sub>} as a matrix M<sub>A</sub> = [e<sub>x</sub>, e<sub>y</sub>], its determinant is non-zero, as shown below:
                            $$det(M_A) = \begin{vmatrix}1&0\\0&1\end{vmatrix} = 1-0 = 1 (\neq0)$$
                            However, if we write B = {v<sub>1</sub>,v<sub>2</sub>} as a matrix M<sub>B</sub> = [v<sub>1</sub>, v<sub>2</sub>], its determinant is zero, as shown below:
                            $$det(M_B) = \begin{vmatrix}1&1\\2&2\end{vmatrix} = 2-2 = 0$$
                            <u>Key Point 1</u>: If the determinant of the matrix representation of the vectors of a given set is zero, the vectors are said to be linearly dependent, and are otherwise called linearly independent.
                          </p>
                          <p>Example 1: Find the values of k for which the vectors (1,1,1,1), (1,3,-2,k), (2,2k-2,-k-2) and (3,k-2,-3,2k+1) are linearly independent in R<sup>4</sup>.
                          </p>
                          <p>Solution 1: The given set of vectors is linearly independent if the determinant of the matrix representation of the vectors is non-zero, which implies:
                          </p>
                          <p> $$\begin{vmatrix}1&1&2&3\\1&3&2k-2&k+2\\1&-2&-k-2&-3\\1&k&3k-1&2k+1\end{vmatrix} \neq0$$
                          </p>
                          <p>Applying the row operations R2 = R2-R1, R2 = R2-R1 , R3 = R3-R1 and calculating the determinant, we get
                            $$k\neq1,5$$
                          </p>

